05857nam a22008415i 9780857455444DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574554447 a10.1515/97808574554442doi  a(DE-B1597)636246  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJC480.A743bH36 2008eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a320.5322200aHannah Arendt and the Uses of History :bImperialism, Nation, Race, and Genocide /ced. by Richard H. King, Dan Stone. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: IMPERIALISM AND COLONIALISM -- tChapter 1 Race Power, Freedom, and the Democracy of Terror in German Racialist Thought -- tChapter 2 Race Thinking and Racism in Hannah Arendt’s The Origins of Totalitarianism -- tChapter 3 When the Real Crime Began -- tChapter 4 Race and Bureaucracy Revisited -- tChapter 5 On Pain of Extinction -- tPART II: NATION AND RACE -- tChapter 6 The Refractory Legacy of Algerian Decolonization -- tChapter 7 Anti-Semitism, the Bourgeoisie, and the Self-Destruction of the Nation-State -- tChapter 8 Post-Totalitarian Elements and Eichmann’s Mentality in the Yugoslav War and Mass Killings -- tPART III: INTELLECTUAL GENEALOGIES AND LEGACIES -- tChapter 9 Hannah Arendt on Totalitarianism -- tChapter 10 Hannah Arendt, Biopolitics, and the Problem of Violence -- tChapter 11 The “Subterranean Stream of Western History” -- tChapter 12 Hannah Arendt and the Old “New Science” -- tChapter 13 The Holocaust and “The Human” -- tConclusion. Arendt between Past and Future -- tSelect Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHannah Arendt (1906-1975) first argued that there were continuities between the age of European imperialism and the age of fascism in Europe in The Origins of Totalitarianism (1951). She claimed that theories of race, notions of racial and cultural superiority, and the right of ‘superior races’ to expand territorially were themes that connected the white settler colonies, the other imperial possessions, and the fascist ideologies of post-Great War Europe. These claims have rarely been taken up by historians. Only in recent years has the work of scholars such as Jürgen Zimmerer and A. Dirk Moses begun to show in some detail that Arendt was correct. This collection does not seek merely to expound Arendt’s opinions on these subjects; rather, it seeks to use her insights as the jumping-off point for further investigations – including ones critical of Arendt – into the ways in which race, imperialism, slavery and genocide are linked, and the ways in which these terms have affected the United States, Europe, and the colonised world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGenocide. 0aImperialism. 0aPolitical violence. 0aRacism. 0aTotalitarianism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBarta, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernasconi, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurthoys, Ned, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuarte, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEaglestone, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGines, Kathryn T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJalušič, Vlasta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoeden-Forgey, Elisa von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/